	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>South Africa seeks duty-free access to EU sugar market </h1>

			
			<h4>
												26 September 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The South African Sugar Association (SASA) has announced that it is actively pursuing talks with the South African government and the EU to conclude an Economic Partnership Agreement (EPA) that would allow South Africa to export a specified quota of sugar duty free to the EU market. This is seen as a short-term arrangement, with the long-term aim being to secure the same full duty-free, quota-free access as other SADC sugar exporters will enjoy once the transitional safeguard clause for sugar lapses, and the current market access arrangements under the IEPAs have been consolidated through the signing of final agreements. Improving access for South African sugar to the EU market is seen as important for enhancing South African sugar sector revenues and reversing the current decline in the sector. </p><p>In the 2009/10 season, South Africa’s drought-affected sugar production fell to a 15-year low of 2.18 million tonnes (with a projected production level for the season up to March 2011 of 2.07 million tonnes). Sugar production has been declining for the past three years. In August SASA Executive Director Trix Trikam told the press, ‘We used to produce an average of 2.5 million tonnes of sugar (annually), but our average these days is around 2.2 million tonnes.’ Trikam added that uncertainty over land reform was ‘discouraging new investment’ in sugar farming. Trikam hopes that with the benefit of improved revenues from quota-restricted, duty-free sales to the EU market, sugar production can be brought back up to an annual average of 2.5 million tonnes.</p><p>Meanwhile, the TRALAC 2009 annual publication ‘Monitoring regional integration in Southern Africa: Yearbook’ contains an article entitled ‘Sugar in South Africa and Swaziland’, which examines the regulatory framework for sugar production in the SACU, in the context of ongoing SACU trade negotiations with Mercosur. It concludes that, on the basis of preliminary economic modelling, liberalisation of the sugar sector would reduce welfare in both South Africa and the rest of the SACU.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
