<a href="http://www.tongaat.co.za/imc/annual_reports/ar_2010/downloads/PDF/tongaat_annual_report_2010.pdf" target="_self">http://www.tongaat.co.za/imc/annual_reports/ar_2010/downloads/PDF/tongaa...</a> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Securing quota-restricted, duty-free access for South African sugar would not only open up access to the EU market for general exports of raw sugar, but would also open up opportunities for the export of both fair-trade and organic sugar. This could be of considerable benefit to the South African smallholder sugar farmers, whose engagement in the industry is being encouraged under black economic empowerment polices, but where the trend is towards the reduction of the number of registered growers.</p><p>Whether this would reverse the current gradual decline in overall South Africa sugar production is unclear. Since 1997 a number of major South African sugar companies have been expanding their operations in neighbouring SADC countries, with this pace of expansion accelerating following the announcement of the EU’s EBA initiative and the establishment of transitional arrangements for the granting of full duty-free, quota-free access for sugar exports to the EU market. Thus it can be found that, whereas in 2001/02 around 57% of the Illovo Group’s sugar production originated in South Africa, by the 2008/09 season this had fallen to 39%, while the contribution to group profits of the South Africa operations had fallen from 42% to 19%. Similarly a review of Tongaat Hulett revenue streams reveals the emergence of a major real estate arm, based on the conversion of high-value sugar land into retirement and holiday home complexes. In 2010 the revenues from the land conversion arm of the business made a greater contribution to the profitability of Tongaat than the South African sugar milling and refining operations. </p><p>Thus, while duty-free, quota-free access may assist in efforts to empower black smallholder sugar growers, it is unclear whether it would be likely to reverse the current slow downward trend in sugar production.</p><p>South African efforts to secure quota-restricted, duty-free access to the EU market need to be seen against the background of the recent EU agreements concluded with Central American and Andean Pact countries and the uneven treatment of agricultural products under the EU-South Africa Trade, Development and Cooperation Agreement (TDCA). Under the TDCA, which was signed in 1999 and had a 12-year implementation period, South Africa committed to eliminating tariffs on 83% of agricultural imports from the EU, with 50% of agricultural import being liberalised within five years and only one-sixth of all agricultural product lines being excluded from the agreement. In contrast, the EU agreed to eliminate tariffs on about 61% of South Africa agricultural exports and established tariff-rate quotas (TRQs) for products accounting for a further 13% of agricultural imports from South Africa. Sugar was noticeably excluded from these TRQ arrangements, despite the inclusion of important sugar-based, value-added food products in the tariff elimination commitments made by South Africa (notably for sweets and chocolates). </p>
		</div>
		
